    "reasoning": "Now I have all the key data. Let me compile the analysis:\n\n**Key Figures:**\n\n1. **FY2025 Connectivity Segment Adjusted EBITDA**: $7,168 million\n2. **FY2025 Consolidated Capex**: $20,737 million\n   - Connectivity segment capex: $4,178 million\n   - AI segment capex: $12,727 million\n   - Space segment capex: $3,832 million\n3. **Q1 2026 AI Capex**: $7,723 million \u2192 Annualized: $7,723 \u00d7 4 = $30,892 million\n\n**Connectivity Segment Adjusted EBITDA vs. its own capex:**\n- Connectivity Adj. EBITDA: $7,168M\n- Connectivity capex: $4,178M\n- Connectivity \"free cash flow proxy\" (Adj. EBITDA - capex): $7,168 - $4,178 = $2,990M\n\n**Comparison:**\n- Connectivity Adj. EBITDA ($7,168M) covers only 34.6% of consolidated capex ($20,737M)\n- Q1 2026 AI capex annualized ($30,892M) is 4.3x the Connectivity Adj. EBITDA\n- Consolidated operating cash flow FY2025: $6,785M \u2014 even less than Connectivity Adj. EBITDA\n\n**Which internal cash source is most capable?**\nThe Connectivity segment is clearly the most capable internal cash source. It generated $7,168M in Adjusted EBITDA against only $4,178M in capex, yielding a ~$2,990M surplus. The Space segment had only $653M in Adjusted EBITDA. The AI segment had negative Adjusted EBITDA of $(1,237)M.\n\n**Risks if Connectivity growth slows:**\n- ARPU dilution (11.2% decline in FY2025, 22.9% in Q1 2026)\n- Subscriber growth may decelerate as markets saturate\n- Competition from terrestrial providers\n- If Connectivity EBITDA growth slows, the company would need to rely even more heavily on external financing (debt/equity) to fund the massive AI capex buildout\n- The $19.6B EchoStar spectrum acquisition adds further capital pressure\n\nLet me calculate a few more things for the analysis.\n",
